                                                            "detail": "<p class=\"font_8\">The Busan Fish Market is divided into two main areas:<br>\nThe main area is a three-story building specializing in various types of fish:<br>\n– Live fish: kept in spacious tanks with both saltwater and freshwater, regularly aerated.<br>\n– Fresh fish: chilled with ice in styrofoam containers.<br>\n– Frozen fish: stored in freezers as fillets or whole fish.<br>\n– Dried fish, squid, and shrimp.<br>\n– Salted fish, fermented fish, and soy sauce fish…<br>\n– Fish that is prepared and cooked on-site for customers at the market.<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">Everything is sold in conditions that ensure food safety and hygiene. There are no flies, no unpleasant odors..<\/p>",
                                                            "detail3": "<p class=\"font_8\">This area sells freshly caught fish displayed on makeshift stands, 20-40 cm above the ground, in a traditional Vietnamese market style. The area remains clean thanks to a well-maintained, rinsed floor with good drainage, and the open-roof structure provides airflow and light, minimizing odors.<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\"><br><\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">Many fish stalls process fish on-site, properly washing them and disposing of waste. Vendors collect fish heads and entrails for animal feed, and the stalls are kept tidy with no clutter. This differs from markets in my hometown, where cleanliness is less maintained.<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\"><br><\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">The market sells fresh fish daily, unlike live seafood stalls that use aeration and water tanks. It stands out for its excellent water supply and drainage, keeping it clean and odor-free. While outdoor selling isn’t ideal in cold weather, the low temperatures help keep the fish fresh.<\/p>",
                                                            "title": "Perspective on Traditional Market Model – Part 1: The fish market in Busan",
                                                            "ngy": "2020-03-20",
                                                            "link-project-case-studies-1-all": "\/project-case-studies-1\/"
                                                        },
                                                        "3a3c6906-494d-423e-9b8a-fcfc9d4aa698": {
                                                            "nh2": "wix:image:\/\/v1\/f6985b_cb5f6e244a5946f88ae3c5e2231384fd~mv2.jpg\/cho.jpg#originWidth=1920&originHeight=1482",
                                                            "detail2": "<p class=\"font_8\">According to general statistics from traditional tier-2 markets, approximately 60-70% of business points are non-fixed stalls, meaning they lack permanent, built-up structures. Most of these stalls sell fresh food products such as meat, fish, vegetables, fruits, and flowers. Since vendors do not have fixed locations, they are required to pay daily market fees, which, when calculated on a monthly basis, often exceed the fees paid by permanent stall owners. However, field surveys in markets across Khánh Hòa reveal that 99% of vendors selling vegetables, meat, and fish operate consistently in the same familiar spots for extended periods—almost \"untouchable.\"<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">This makes it difficult for market management to enforce new regulations on sector arrangement and relocate vendors to fixed areas.<\/p>",
                                                            "nh3": "wix:image:\/\/v1\/f6985b_92162b7ae7f74200aa20f40eac8fb794~mv2.jpg\/014bab7t588uj1694331291691.jpg#originWidth=800&originHeight=450",
                                                            "detail21": "<p class=\"font_8\"><strong>Image 1: Dam Market Nha Trang <\/strong>&nbsp;(<em>cre: Internet<\/em>)<\/p>",
                                                            "description": "<p class=\"font_8\">In Part 1: The Fish Market in Busan, we explored a fish market model from our neighboring country. In this part, let's compare and reflect on the situation of fish markets in Vietnam.<\/p>",
                                                            "_id": "3a3c6906-494d-423e-9b8a-fcfc9d4aa698",
                                                            "_owner": "a6d944a9-a820-4390-9df2-fd561836d0b7",
                                                            "_createdDate": {
                                                                "$date": "2024-11-05T12:48:46.273Z"
                                                            },
                                                            "description1": "Curious about how Vietnam's traditional fish markets compare to those in other countries? Discover the challenges they face and why improving these markets could be the key to attracting more domestic customers.",
                                                            "title1": "<h5 class=\"font_5\"><strong>The neglect of traditional markets in Vietnam<\/strong><\/h5>",
                                                            "link-project-case-studies-all": "\/project-case-studies\/",
                                                            "_updatedDate": {
                                                                "$date": "2025-09-11T14:56:36.705Z"
                                                            },
                                                            "detail1112": "<p class=\"font_8\"><strong>Image 3: One of fish stalls in the market <\/strong>(<em>cre: Internet<\/em>)<\/p>",
                                                            "link-project-case-studies-title": "\/project-case-studies\/dong-tam-market",
                                                            "nhProject": "wix:image:\/\/v1\/f6985b_bc9a312644984c4fa1e033b897315784~mv2.jpg\/cho-dam-nha-trang-9.jpg#originWidth=700&originHeight=468",
                                                            "_manualSort_38639d25-339a-47b8-99d3-6711297ff4c1": "5",
                                                            "detail211": "<p class=\"font_8\"><strong>Image 2: Xom Moi Market Nha Trang<\/strong> (<em>cre: Khanh Hoa News<\/em>)<\/p>",
                                                            "title11": "<h5 class=\"font_5\"><strong>Difficulty in managing and reorganizing market stalls<\/strong><\/h5>",
                                                            "detail212": "<h5 class=\"font_5\"><strong>Challenges faced by fish markets in Vietnam<\/strong><\/h5>",
                                                            "nh1": "wix:image:\/\/v1\/f6985b_3d30378a3a75474888339b403d424371~mv2.jpg\/c%C4%91.jpg#originWidth=686&originHeight=386",
                                                            "detail": "<p class=\"font_8\">While the Busan Fish Market is entirely designed to serve consumers, fish markets in Vietnam are often seen as temporary trading spaces, lacking long-term investment and development. We continue to overlook the reality that makeshift, patched-up canopies have remained unchanged—day after day, year after year, from one economic development plan to the next. These temporary stalls, despite their instability, supply a vast amount of fresh food daily. Their products are often the freshest (as they lack storage facilities) and the most affordable (as competitive pricing is essential to survive against larger stalls and supermarkets).&nbsp;<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\"><br><\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">Countless university graduates and PhDs have been raised thanks to these humble market stalls. Yet, upon achieving success, few contribute to improving the very markets that nurtured them. Instead of being developed, traditional markets are deteriorating, neglected, and struggling to compete in an increasingly aggressive market economy.<\/p>",
                                                            "detail3": "<p class=\"font_8\">In Vietnam, summer temperatures can reach 37-38°C. To keep fish fresh, vendors must continuously ice or aerate them. However, fish stalls are often hot and cramped due to the high density of buyers and sellers, especially since fish and meat are staple foods in daily meals. The inconveniences of fish markets—ranging from strong odors and tight spaces to poor hygiene conditions and food safety concerns—have led many homemakers to switch to buying fish at supermarkets or even replacing it with meat. Meanwhile, domestic businesses face significant challenges in exporting seafood. Instead of focusing solely on foreign markets, why not invest in improving the quality of traditional markets to better tap into the domestic market?<\/p>",
                                                            "title": "Perspective on Traditional Market Model – Part 2: The market in Vietnam",
                                                            "ngy": "2020-04-03",
                                                            "link-project-case-studies-1-all": "\/project-case-studies-1\/"
                                                        },
                                                        "25f2bb4e-0bc1-4a5c-8fba-daf0c2c1d9d4": {
                                                            "nh2": "wix:image:\/\/v1\/f6985b_545dfe1692674075bfdf64a9a17085b8~mv2.jpg\/Cho2_edited.jpg#originWidth=750&originHeight=533",
                                                            "detail2": "<p class=\"font_8\">When shopping for food, it's usually housewives, and for fashion, it's mostly the younger generation. Men rarely visit markets, so women are the primary shoppers. On average, a tier-2 market sees 1,000-1,200 visitors daily, 365 days a year, with each visit lasting about 45 minutes. Despite the high volume, the market conditions are often temporary, dilapidated, unsanitary, dark, and damp. Why not invest in better infrastructure and services?<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\"><br><\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">It's not about a lack of funds. An ideal market just needs a good drainage system, a well-ventilated roof (due to Vietnam's hot, humid climate), clean restrooms, and tidy, well-lit, and ventilated stalls. There's no need for the luxury of shopping malls or supermarkets.<\/p>",
                                                            "detail21": "<p class=\"font_8\"><strong>Image 1: <\/strong>&nbsp;(<em>cre: Internet<\/em>)<\/p>",
                                                            "description": "<p class=\"font_8\">Previous part: Part 2 – Fish Markets in Vietnam<\/p>\n<p class=\"font_8\">Surveys at rural markets like Vinh Luong and Duc My show that people prefer larger city-center markets for high-value goods like clothing and electronics.<\/p>",
